The '''Flamanville Nuclear Power Plant''' is located at [[Flamanville, Manche]], [[France]] on the [[Cotentin Peninsula]]. The [[power plant]] houses three [[pressurized water reactor]]s (PWRs). Units 1 and 2, rated at 1.33 [[GWe|GW<sub>e</sub>]] net each and based on a Westinghouse design,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Westinghouse sells French nuclear stake |journal=Chemical & Engineering News |year=1976 |volume=54 |issue=2 |pages=5|doi=10.1021/cen-v054n002.p005 |quote=Westinghouse will continue to receive license royalties at present rates on the existing and planned nuclear reactors designed around its pressurized-water reactor system.}}</ref> were ordered following the [[Nuclear power in France#Messmer Plan|Messmer Plan]] and deliver full power since 1987. Unit 3 is an [[EPR (nuclear reactor)|EPR]] unit with  a [[nameplate capacity]] of 1.65 [[GWe|GW<sub>e</sub>]] which was connected to the [[Electrical grid|grid]] in December 2024<ref name="yahoo2024">{{Cite news |title=Edf: Update on the Flamanville EPR: the reactor produces its first electrons on the national electricity grid |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/edf-flamanville-epr-reactor-produces-111800219.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnLw&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAANGcQoIykYf4T-ntg3O7j87uMfsfijK5ee_y2MXh_-TCTGa8JR7FVw2Ujv_wt2Dt6FQUPg9Prfz8D0fS6OGfqGaHhr24SnpO0SlPA1KPww_UCTAVCAUo94Yz78tRLQDvCmnJRBWT_WholJoltjf-fnBq4VO8I0rFRnlybTORqmdH}}</ref> and reached full power in December 2025. The power plant produced 18.9 TWh of energy in 2005, which amounted to 4% of the electricity production in France. In 2006 there were 671 workers regularly working at the plant. In 2023, 11,7 TWh was produced with 1400 regular workers.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024 |title=La centrale nucléaire de Flamanville |url=https://www.edf.fr/sites/groupe/files/2024-02/FLA%20Fiche%20presse%202024_vdef.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250620011202/https://www.edf.fr/sites/groupe/files/2024-02/FLA%20Fiche%20presse%202024_vdef.pdf |archive-date=20 June 2025 |access-date= |website=www.edf.fr |page=2 |language=fr |url-status=live }}</ref>

Construction of unit 3 began in 2007 with its commercial introduction scheduled for 2012. [[Areva]], the company in charge of the project, proved unable to manage it (just like [[Olkiluoto Nuclear Power Plant#Unit 3|Olkiluoto 3]]), leading to the ultimate demise of the company. Various safety problems have been raised, including weakness in the steel used in the reactor.<ref>Jennifer Rankin. [https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/jul/27/flamanville-france-edf-nuclear-reactor-hinkley-point-c Flamanville: France's beleaguered forerunner to Hinkley Point C], ''The Guardian'', 27 July 2016.</ref> In July 2019, further delays were announced, pushing back the commercial introduction date to the end of 2022.<ref name="AF">{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/snag-hit-french-nuclear-power-station-delayed-further-082444469.html |newspaper=Agence France Presse |title=Snag-hit new French nuclear power station delayed by further 3 years |date=29 July 2019}}</ref><ref name="wnanews">{{cite web |url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/EDF-warns-of-added-costs-of-Flamanville-EPR-weld-r |title=EDF warns of added costs of Flamanville EPR weld repairs |date=9 October 2019 |website=World Nuclear News}}</ref> {{as of|2020|}} the project was more than five times over budget.<ref name="FL"/> In January 2022, more delays were announced, with fuel loading continuing until mid-2023,<ref name="montel-20220112"/><ref name="ED"/> and again in December 2022, delaying fuel loading to early 2024.<ref name="wnn-20221219"/> Fuel loading was completed in May 2024.<ref>{{Cite news
 | url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Fuel-loading-completed-at-French-EPR
 | work=World Nuclear News
 | date=24 May 2024
 | title=Fuel loading completed at France's Flamanville 3 EPR
 | access-date=1 August 2024
 }}</ref> The reactor eventually started up in early September 2024<ref>{{cite news |title=France's newest nuclear reactor shuts itself down |url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20240905-new-french-nuclear-reactor-enters-automatic-shutdown |access-date=5 September 2024 |publisher=France 24 |date=5 September 2024}}</ref> and was connected to the grid at 11:48 AM on 21 December 2024.<ref name="yahoo2024"/>

==Unit 1 & 2==

=== History ===
During the 1970s, Flamanville was one of the proposed construction sites for the French civil nuclear program. A 1975 poll of local inhabitants showed 63.7% in favor of the project.

Following a public inquiry, the formal [[Déclaration d'utilité publique|declaration of public utility]] was published in 1977, in time for a January 1978 groundbreaking. The official start of construction was recorded as December 1979 for Unit 1 and May 1980 for Unit 2. First criticality was achieved in September 1985 and June 1986, with connections to the grid in December 1985 and July 1986 and full commercial operation in December 1986 and March 1987.<ref name="PR">{{Cite web |title=PRIS - Reactor Details. Flamanville Unit 1 |url=https://pris.iaea.org/PRIS/CountryStatistics/ReactorDetails.aspx?current=202 |access-date=2025-07-07 |website=pris.iaea.org}}</ref><ref name="RD">{{Cite web |title=PRIS - Reactor Details. Flamanville Unit 2 |url=https://pris.iaea.org/PRIS/CountryStatistics/ReactorDetails.aspx?current=203 |access-date=2025-07-07 |website=pris.iaea.org}}</ref>

=== Characteristics ===
Units 1 and 2 are Generation II [[pressurized water reactor]]s of hybrid design, with a nuclear island of [[Nuclear power in France#1300 MWe class (P4 and P'4 designs)|type P4]] and the conventional / turbine island of type P'4.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2021 |title=Poursuite de fonctionnement des réacteurs n°1 et n°2 de la centrale nucléaire de Flamanville après leur deuxième réexamen periodique |url=https://www.asn.fr/Media/Files/00-Publications/rapport-flamanville-reacteurs-n-1-et-2-vd2 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221002072628/https://www.asn.fr/content/download/180341/file/Rapport%20-%20Flamanville%20r%C3%A9acteurs%20n%C2%B01%20et%202%20-%20VD2.pdf |archive-date=October 2, 2022 |access-date=July 6, 2025 |website=[[Autorité de sûreté nucléaire]]}}</ref>

The reactor coolant systems (reactor vessel, steam generators, reactor coolant pumps) were furnished by [[Framatome]]. The two turbine islands (steam turbines, turbogenerators, auxiliary systems, and secondary-side pumps) were provided by [[Alstom#Power generation|Alstom]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2012 |title=Arabelle Steam Turbine for Nuclear Power Plant |url=http://www.alstom.com/Global/Power/Resources/Documents/Brochures/arabell-steam-turbine-nuclear-power-plants-performance-boost.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905072444/http://www.alstom.com/Global/Power/Resources/Documents/Brochures/arabell-steam-turbine-nuclear-power-plants-performance-boost.pdf |archive-date=2012-09-05 |access-date=2025-07-07 |website=www.alstom.com |page=10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Alstom confirme sa position de leader pour les îlots conventionnels de centrale nucléaire |url=https://www.alstom.com/fr/press-releases-news/2008/6/alstom-confirme-position-leader-ilots-conventionnels-centrale-nucleaire |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250522110355/https://www.alstom.com/fr/press-releases-news/2008/6/alstom-confirme-position-leader-ilots-conventionnels-centrale-nucleaire |archive-date=May 22, 2025 |access-date=2025-07-07 |website=Alstom |language=fr}}</ref>

The reactors of units 1 and 2 can produce 3,817 MWt. Gross electric power from the generator is 1,382 MWe, and net electric power, after station consumption, is 1,330 MWe, with a thermal efficiency of 34.8%.<ref name="PR"/><ref name="RD"/> In 2025, Units 1 and 2 employed approximately 1,100 EDF employees and contractors, and supplied more than half the electricity required in the [[Normandy]] region.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2025-05-20 |title=La centrale nucléaire de Flamanville 1-2 |url=https://www.edf.fr/centrale-nucleaire-flamanville |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250614142800/https://www.edf.fr/centrale-nucleaire-flamanville |archive-date=2025-06-14 |access-date=2025-07-07 |work=EDF FR |language=fr}}</ref>

==Unit 3==
{{See also|EPR (nuclear reactor)#Flamanville 3 (France)}}

Construction of a new reactor, Flamanville 3, began on 4 December 2007.<ref name="wnn041207">{{Cite news
 | url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/newsarticle.aspx?id=14496
 | work=World Nuclear News
 | date=4 December 2007
 | title=Construction of Flamanville EPR begins
 | access-date=19 March 2011
 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014020153/http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/newsarticle.aspx?id=14496
 | archive-date=14 October 2014
 | url-status=dead
 }}</ref> The new unit is an [[Areva]] [[European Pressurized Reactor]] type and is planned to have a [[nameplate capacity]] of 1,650&nbsp;MWe. EDF estimated the cost at €3.3&nbsp;billion<ref name="wnn041207"/> and stated it would start commercial operations in 2012, after construction lasting 54 months.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sectionCode=132&storyCode=2048041 |title=Flamanville 3 concrete poured |newspaper=Nuclear Engineering International |date=6 December 2007 |access-date=1 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613091002/http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sectionCode=132&storyCode=2048041 |archive-date=13 June 2011 }}</ref> The latest cost estimate (July 2020) is at €19.1 billion, with commissioning planned tentatively at the end of 2022.<ref name="FL">{{Cite news|date=2020-07-09|title=" Echec opérationnel " et " dérive des coûts " : la gestion de l'EPR, réacteur nucléaire de troisième génération, décriée par la Cour de comptes|language=fr|work=Le Monde.fr|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/economie/article/2020/07/09/nucleaire-la-cour-des-comptes-ereinte-l-epr_6045707_3234.html|access-date=2020-07-09}}</ref><ref name="AF"/>

On 3 December 2012, EDF announced that the estimated costs have escalated to €8.5 billion ($11&nbsp;billion), and the completion of construction was being delayed to 2016.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2012/12/03/le-cout-de-l-epr-de-flamanville-encore-revu-a-la-hausse_1799417_3244.html | agency=Le Monde | date=3 December 2012 | title=Le coût de l'EPR de Flamanville encore revu à la hausse| access-date=4 December 2012}}</ref> The next day the Italian power company [[Enel]] announced it was relinquishing its 12.5% stake in the project, and five future EPRs. They would be reimbursed for their project stake of €613 million plus interest.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.powermag.com/enel-drops-participation-in-flamanville-epr-as-project-costs-soar-by-2-6b/ |title=Enel Drops Participation in Flamanville EPR as Project Costs Soar by $2.6B |newspaper=POWER |date=6 December 2012 |access-date=14 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.enel.com/en-GB/media/press_releases/enel-and-edf-terminate-their-cooperation-on-epr-in-france/r/1656525 |title=Enel and Edf Terminate their cooperation on EPR in France |publisher=Enel |date=4 December 2012 |access-date=14 August 2013 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924000833/http://www.enel.com/en-GB/media/press_releases/enel-and-edf-terminate-their-cooperation-on-epr-in-france/r/1656525 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

In November 2014, EDF announced that completion of construction was delayed to 2017 due to delays in component delivery by [[Areva]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/adc90b3e-6f67-11e4-8d86-00144feabdc0 |title=EDF in fresh delay for flagship nuclear plant |author=Michael Stothard |newspaper=Financial Times |date=18 November 2014 |access-date=21 November 2014}}</ref>

In April 2015, Areva informed the French nuclear regulator, [[Autorité de sûreté nucléaire]] (ASN), that anomalies had been detected in the reactor vessel steel, causing "lower than expected mechanical toughness values".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/RS-Flamanville-EPR-vessel-anomalies-under-scrutiny-0704154.html |title=Flamanville EPR vessel anomalies under scrutiny |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=7 April 2015 |access-date=11 April 2015}}</ref><ref>http://www.asn.fr: [http://www.asn.fr/Informer/Actualites/EPR-de-Flamanville-anomalies-de-fabrication-de-la-cuve Anomalies de fabrication de la cuve de l’EPR de Flamanville]. Communiqué de presse, 7 April 2015</ref> [[Segolene Royal]], [[Ministry of Ecology, Sustainable Development and Energy|Minister of Ecology, Sustainable Development and Energy]] in the [[Second Valls Government]], asked the producer for further details and possible consequences.<ref>8. April 2015: [http://www.greenetvert.fr/2015/04/08/nucleaire-une-nouvelle-anomalie-detectee-sur-lepr-de-flamanville/82548 Nucléaire: une nouvelle anomalie détectée sur l’EPR de Flamanville]</ref>

Various safety problems have been raised, including weakness in the steel used in the reactor<ref>Jennifer Rankin. Flamanville: France's beleaguered forerunner to Hinkley Point C, ''The Guardian'', 27 July 2016.</ref> together with heterogeneity of the steel alloy forged high integrity components used in the reactor pressure vessel,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.largeassociates.com/CZ3233/Note_LargeAndAssociates_EN_26092016.pdf|title=Review: Irregularities and Anomalies Relating to the Forged Components of le Creusot Forge, 26 September 2016|access-date=15 January 2017|archive-date=16 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116180855/http://www.largeassociates.com/CZ3233/Note_LargeAndAssociates_EN_26092016.pdf|url-status=dead}}</ref> that have also been shown to be present in Japanese-sourced components that have entered the French nuclear equipment supply chain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.largeassociates.com/CZ3235/R3235-A1FINAL2410-16.pdf|title=Review: Irregularities and Anomalies Relating to the Nuclear Reactor Primary Coolant Circuit Components Installed in Japanese Nuclear Power Plants - Part 1 French Carbon Anomaly Correlation to Japanese Nuclear Power Plants=24 October 2016|access-date=15 January 2017|archive-date=16 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116181015/http://www.largeassociates.com/CZ3235/R3235-A1FINAL2410-16.pdf|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.largeassociates.com/CZ3235/R3235-A2-12-12-16-FINAL.pdf|title=Review: Irregularities and Anomalies Relating to the Nuclear Reactor Primary Coolant Circuit Components Installed in Japanese Nuclear Power Plants - Concluding Parts 2 & 3 - Potential Flawed Components Resident in Japanese Nuclear Power Plants=10 December 2016|access-date=15 January 2017|archive-date=16 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116181053/http://www.largeassociates.com/CZ3235/R3235-A2-12-12-16-FINAL.pdf|url-status=dead}}</ref> The safety of the Flamanville EPR plant has also been questioned due to the danger of flooding of the kind experienced during the [[1999 Blayais Nuclear Power Plant flood]].<ref>[http://deciphering-fukushima.blogs.sciencesetavenir.fr/tag/monique%20sen%C3%A9 The great lesson France has to learn from Fukushima] Deciphering Fukushima, published 2011-03-08, accessed 8 May 2012</ref> In June 2015 multiple faults in cooling system safety valves were discovered by ASN.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/11662889/Faulty-valves-in-new-generation-EPR-nuclear-reactor-pose-meltdown-risk-inspectors-warn.html |title=Faulty valves in new-generation EPR nuclear reactor pose meltdown risk, inspectors warn |author=Henry Samuel |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=9 June 2015 |access-date=9 July 2015}}</ref>

In September 2015, EDF announced that the estimated costs had escalated to €10.5&nbsp;billion, and the start-up of the reactor was delayed to the fourth quarter of 2018.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Not stated--> |title=Flamanville EPR: optimised project management and a new timetable |url=https://www.edf.fr/en/edf/flamanville-epr-optimised-project-management-and-a-new-timetable |location=Flamanville, France |publisher=EDF |date=September 3, 2015 |access-date=2023-06-16}}</ref> The delays of Unit 3 of Flamanville received additional attention when in December 2016 ''[[The Economist]]'' reported that the British loan guarantees for [[Hinkley Point C nuclear power station|Hinkley Point C]] require Unit 3 to be operational by 2020, that the regulator will rule on the future of Unit 3 mid-2017 and that one possible outcome of this ruling can delay its opening far beyond 2018, thus jeopardizing the British loan guarantees thereby preventing EDF from building the EPRs at Hinkley Point.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.economist.com/news/business/21711087-electricit-de-france-has-had-shut-down-18-its-58-nuclear-reactors-frances-nuclear-energy |title= France's nuclear-energy champion is in turmoil |newspaper= [[The Economist]] |date= 3 December 2016 |access-date= 4 December 2016}}</ref>

In February 2017, renewed delays in the construction of the EPR-reactors at [[Taishan Nuclear Power Plant]] prompted EDF to state that Flamanville 3 remains on schedule to start operations by the end of 2018, assuming it receives regulator approval.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/international-business/edf-confirms-flamanville-timetable-after-taishan-epr-delay/articleshow/57294950.cms |title= EDF confirms Flamanville timetable after Taishan EPR delay |work= [[Times of India]] |date= 22 February 2017 |access-date= 9 March 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, the French regulator issued a provisional ruling that Flamanville 3 is safe to start.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/RS-French-regulator-says-Flamanville-3-is-safe-to-start-29061701.html |website= [[world-nuclear-news.org]] |title= French regulator says Flamanville 3 is safe to start |date= 28 June 2017 |access-date= 3 July 2017}}</ref>

In January 2018, cold functional tests were completed.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Flamanville EPR completes key pre-operational tests - World Nuclear News |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Flamanville-EPR-completes-key-pre-operational-tests-0901184.html |access-date=2023-06-16 |website=world-nuclear-news.org}}</ref> In February, EDF found that some secondary cooling circuit welds did not meet specifications, causing EDF to carry out further checks and issue a report. Following this, ASN requested EDF to extend the welding checks to other systems. Hot functional tests had to be postponed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.neimagazine.com/news/newspossible-reprieve-for-fessenheim-due-to-further-flamanville-delays-6175762 |title=Possible reprieve for Fessenheim due to further Flamanville delays |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=4 June 2018 |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref>

In July 2018, EDF further delayed fuel loading to Q4 2019 and increased the project's cost estimate by a further €400 million ($467.1 million USD).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/economie/article/2019/06/20/nucleaire-nouveau-retard-confirme-pour-l-epr-de-flamanville_5478853_3234.html|title=Nucléaire : l'EPR de Flamanville connaît de nouveaux retards et ne pourra pas démarrer avant 2022|date=20 June 2019|access-date=20 June 2019|language=fr}}</ref> The latest project cost estimates by EDF amounted to €10.9 billion ($12.75 billion USD), three times the original cost estimates. Hot testing was pushed back to the end of 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/EDF-warns-of-added-costs-of-Flamanville-EPR-weld-r|title=EDF warns of added costs of Flamanville EPR weld repairs|date=9 October 2019|work=World Nuclear News}}</ref> In January 2019, a further one-month delay in hot testing was announced.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsedf-gives-update-on-flamanville-3-6956612 |title=EDF gives update on Flamanville 3 |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=25 January 2019 |access-date=30 January 2019}}</ref>

In June 2019, the regulator ASN determined that eight welds in steam transfer pipes passing through the two-wall containment, that EDF had hoped to repair after startup, must be repaired before the reactor is commissioned.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Weld-repairs-to-delay-Flamanville-EPR-start-up |title=Weld repairs to delay Flamanville EPR start-up |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=20 June 2019 |access-date=21 June 2019}}</ref> On 29 June 2019, it was announced that the start-up was once again being pushed back, making it unlikely it could be started before the end of 2022.<ref name="AF"/> It is estimated the repairs will add €1.5 billion to the costs, bringing the total to €12.4 billion.<ref name="wnanews"/> Further cost increases due to additional time needed to repair 110 defective welds have increased the cost to €12.7 billion.<ref name="montel-20220112">{{cite news |url=https://www.montelnews.com/news/1292315/edf-delays-flamanville-start-up-to-end-2023-on-weld-issue |title=EDF delays Flamanville start-up to end 2023 on weld issue |last=Boselli |first=Muriel |website=Montel |date=12 January 2022 |access-date=13 January 2022}}</ref><ref name="ED">{{Cite web|date=2022-01-12|title=Point d'actualité sur l'EPR de Flamanville|url=https://www.edf.fr/groupe-edf/espaces-dedies/journalistes/tous-les-communiques-de-presse/point-d-actualite-sur-l-epr-de-flamanville-0|access-date=2022-01-12|website=EDF France|language=fr}}</ref>

In July 2020, the French [[Cour des Comptes (France)|Cour des Comptes]] finalised an eighteen-month in-depth analysis of the project, concluding that the total estimated cost reaches up to €19.1 billion. The severe delays incurred additional financing costs, as well as added taxes and levies. In a response, EDF did not dispute the findings of the court.<ref name="FL"/> In the same month, France's energy minister [[Barbara Pompili]] noted the high costs and delays, calling the project "a mess".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Eales|first=Chris|date=23 July 2020|title=French "EPR is a mess" – energy minister|work=Montel News|url=https://www.montelnews.com/en/story/french-epr-is-a-mess--energy-minister/1133707}}</ref>

In December 2022, EDF announced a further delay of at least six months with an estimated cost increase of €500 million due to more work to establish a new process for the [[Heat treating#Stress relieving|stress relieving heat treatment]] of some welds close to sensitive equipment. Estimated total costs increased to €13.2 billion.<ref name="wnn-20221219">{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Further-delay-to-Flamanville-EPR-start-up |title=Further delay to Flamanville EPR start up |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=19 December 2022 |access-date=20 December 2022}}</ref> Fuel loading started on 8 May 2024 and has been completed on 22 May 2024.<ref>{{Cite press release |last=EDF |date=2024-05-08 |title=EDF: Update on the Flamanville EPR |url=https://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2024/05/08/2878061/0/en/EDF-Update-on-the-Flamanville-EPR.html |access-date=2024-06-11 |website=GlobeNewswire News Room |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Fuel-loading-completed-at-French-EPR |title=Fuel loading completed at France's Flamanville 3 EPR |website=World Nuclear News |date=24 May 2024 |access-date=11 June 2024}}</ref>

On 3 September 2024, the reactor started test operation, but the following day it shut down automatically, possibly due to a configuration error.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/flamanville-epr-in-automatic-shut-down/ |title=Flamanville EPR in automatic shut down |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=10 September 2024 |access-date=12 September 2024}}</ref> The reactor suffered a second automatic shutdown on September 17.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/frances-edf-investigates-second-automatic-shutdown-flamanville-3-reactor-2024-09-17/ |title=France's EDF investigates second automatic shutdown at Flamanville 3 reactor |publisher=Reuters |date=17 September 2024 |access-date=19 September 2024}}</ref>

On 21 December 2024, the reactor was connected to the national grid, initially producing 100 MW of power.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.barrons.com/news/france-s-most-powerful-nuclear-reactor-finally-comes-on-stream-a3af54c4/ |title=France's Most Powerful Nuclear Reactor Finally Comes On Stream |publisher=Barrons |date=21 December 2024 |access-date=21 December 2024}}</ref> After commissioning tests during the first year of operation,<ref>{{cite web | title=Delay in Flamanville 3 attaining full power | date=4 August 2025 | url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/articles/delay-in-flamanville-3-attaining-full-power }}</ref> the reactor reached full power for the first time on 14 December 2025.<ref>{{cite web | title=Flamanville 3 attains full power | date=14  December 2025 | url=https://lesechos-comfi.lesechos.fr/press-release/credit-cooperatif-epa-edf-update-on-the-flamanville-epr-the-reactor-has-reached-100-of-nuclear-thermal-power-W7fljArQRAd }}</ref>

On 5 May 2026, the reactor of Flamanville 3 officially entered into comercial operation marking the end of the commissioning stage.

